title: Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop, ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Railroad Stations. Columbia and Puget Sound. Railroad depot and machine shop. Built 1876?, demolished by fire June 6, 1889? Photo by Asahel Curtis." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Another picture showing the original South School (Main Street) some years after its erection in 1873.  The center building on the trestle is Seattle's first depot, on the Railroad originally constructed to bring coal from Renton and Newcastle.  This is the present site of the “Union Depot” on King street.  The lumber shed of the Retize sawmill shows to the left.  The tracks ran along what is now King street.  The Grant Street bridge later followed this route to the south.”
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. King St.

title: Classes of South School, opening day, September 2, 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Group. Classes of South School, opening day, Sept. 2, 1889. Identified on balcony: Thomas Burke, George Orth, Beckie Schoenfelt, Florence Stowell (Hubbart) teacher, Nellie, Mamie and Don Cowie, Herb Schoenfelt, Blanche Croffut, May Ryther, Alice Carey, Sarah Gottstein, Mamie Chamberlain, Lulu Fuller." Transcribed from back of photograph: “It was a “gala” day - and justified this picture of school, pupils and teachers, as they prepared to enter the new SOUTH SCHOOL for the first classes at the opening of the Fall term on the first Monday of September in 1889.  This and the Central were the city's first brick schools.  On the balcony are Thomas Burke, George Orth, Beckie Schoenfelt, teacher Florence Stowell, Nellie, Mamie and Don Cowie, Herb Schoenfelt, Blanche Croffut, May Ryther, Alice Carey, Sarah Gottstein, Mamie Chamberlain, Lulu Fuller, among others.  This picture through the courtesy of the late Florence Stowell Hubbart.”
intersection: 12th Ave. S. and S. Weller St.

title: King County Courthouse, ca. 1882
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Buildings. King County Court House. First. 3rd Ave. and Yesler Way . Built 1860; acquired by Seattle 1891. Exterior. Frame. View of front from left side. Ca. 1882. Public school classes were held here from 1864 to 1868." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Public School classes were held in this, originally the “old” County Building, at Third and Jefferson, from 1864-1868, before the community had its first school structure.  Teachers during these years included Dillis B. Ward, Mrs. Wm. Hammond, Mrs. Emma Preston, Mrs. Mary A. Smith, and Miss Carrie Bacon." Building served as the King County Courthouse and then Seattle's first City Hall.  Located on 3rd Ave. between Yesler Way and Jefferson Street.
intersection: 3rd Ave. and Yesler Way

title: Seattle's first City Hall, March 6, 1905
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Buildings. Seattle City Hall. First. 3rd Ave. and Yesler Way (later 4208 E Madison) Built 1860; acquired from King County 1891; demolished in 1940. Exterior. Frame. View of front from right side. March 6, 1905. So many enlargements, additions and alterations were added to the original building that it was dubbed "Katzenjammer Castle."" Building served as the King County Courthouse and then Seattle's first City Hall.  Located on 3rd Ave. between Yesler Way and Jefferson Street.
intersection: 3rd Ave. and Yesler Way

title: South School baseball team, 1890
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Group. Baseball team, South School. Spring, 1890. Standing: John Hermanson, Lorne Bane, Henry Baumgart, Charles Christensen, Andrew Brennan, Ab Williams. Center: Chester Smart. Seated: George Sidney, William Steiner, Ben Bloom." Transcribed from back of photo: “SOUTH SCHOOL'S “FIRST” BASEBALL TEAM What can be described as the South School's first baseball team was undoubtedly the group photographed above, organized among the students of the school in the spring of 1890. Copy of the photograph was furnished by Floyd Croft, who can be described as the team manager and scorer. With the erection of the Rainier, the T.T. Minor, the Pontius and the Mercer Schools in 1890, interschool competition was inaugurated in 1891.”
